cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "RePERS — operating layer for multi-agent repository work"
message: "If you reference this harness in academic work or technical writing, please cite it."
type: software
authors:
  - name: "coolsocket"
    website: "https://github.com/coolsocket"
repository-code: "https://github.com/coolsocket/repers"
url: "https://github.com/coolsocket/repers"
abstract: >-
  A contract layer for AI agents working on the same codebase at the same time,
  and for handing the resulting work off across teams, repos, and AI vendors.
  Where agent runtimes (LangGraph, CrewAI, OpenHands, Devin, etc.) execute LLM
  calls, RePERS sits above any runtime to coordinate them: preflight (capability
  discovery as shared memory across agents) → plan as a DAG with target-file
  isolation → parallel dispatch with collision guards → reviewer-on-join →
  evidence-based ship → portable release-pack handoff. The harness ships with a
  router that picks the right slice of the pipeline per task — for trivial work
  (single-file bug, test pins the answer) it tells the calling agent to skip the
  harness entirely, because a real benchmark on sqlfluff measured 5.8× wall-clock
  overhead with no quality lift when the harness was force-fitted onto a 4-line
  patch. The value scales with codebase maturity: at the small end (greenfield,
  solo) the overhead dominates; in a 200k-LOC monorepo with parallel multi-agent
  work the dispatch contract prevents N agents from clobbering each other; at
  enterprise scale the JSON evidence chain becomes an auditable handoff
  protocol between teams using different AI vendors; in cross-org settings the
  release-pack archive lets a receiving repo re-verify another team's work
  independently without trusting the sender's vendor. The dispatch contract is
  proven by a deterministic offline fixture before any live agent runs; every
  stage emits JSON evidence so a later agent (or human reviewer) can pick up
  where the previous one stopped. Ships a 25-entry capability registry, a
  Codex/Claude plugin with five skills (init / route / bug-hunt / release-pack
  / sinkin), a Git pre-commit hook, and four install fixtures proving cross-repo
  adoption from three different start states. Runtime is stdlib-Python only;
  the contracts are AI-agnostic by design.
